<section class="section">
  <h2>6. Feature Discovery</h2>
  
  <h3>Accessing the Daily Wage Calculator</h3>
  
  <p><span class="citation" data-source="zendesk" data-ref="14243704039185">The Daily Wage Calculator is accessed from Settings → Payroll → Daily Wage Calculation</span>. Follow the navigation path below to locate this feature.</p>

  <ol class="step-list">
    <li>Log in to your Bayzat account with Super Admin or Payroll Manager credentials</li>
    <li>Click the <strong>Settings</strong> icon in the main navigation menu</li>
    <li>Select <strong>Payroll</strong> from the settings menu</li>
    <li>Click on <strong>Daily Wage Calculation</strong> to access the main configuration interface</li>
  </ol>

  <figure class="screenshot-container">
    <img src="validation/screenshots/07-daily-wage-calculation-table.png" alt="Daily Wage Calculation table showing salary proration, EOS leave encashment, and unpaid leave deduction sections" class="screenshot">
    <figcaption>Feature Discovery - Daily Wage Calculation section accessible from Settings > Payroll with table displaying salary proration, EOS leave encashment, and unpaid leave deduction options</figcaption>
  </figure>

  <h3>Related Configuration Areas</h3>
  
  <p>The Daily Wage Calculator integrates with several other configuration areas. You may need to access these depending on your setup needs:</p>

  <div class="grid-3">
    <div class="card">
      <h4>End of Service Eligibility</h4>
      <p><strong>Path:</strong> Settings > Payroll > End of Service Eligibility</p>
      <p style="color: #6B7280; font-size: 14px;">Configure leave encashment policies for end-of-service calculations</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
      <h4>Leave Policies</h4>
      <p><strong>Path:</strong> Settings > Leaves > Leave Policies</p>
      <p style="color: #6B7280; font-size: 14px;">Set up unpaid leave deduction calculations</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
      <h4>Payroll Settings</h4>
      <p><strong>Path:</strong> Settings > Payroll</p>
      <p style="color: #6B7280; font-size: 14px;">Access all payroll-related configurations</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="section">
  <h2>7. Setup Process</h2>
  
  <h3>Step-by-Step Configuration</h3>

  <h4>Phase 1: Select Calculation Base</h4>
  
  <p><span class="citation" data-source="zendesk" data-ref="14243704039185">The Daily Wage Calculator allows you to select a calculation base from three options: calendar days, working days, or custom days</span>.</p>

  <ol class="step-list">
    <li>Navigate to <strong>Settings > Payroll > Daily Wage Calculation</strong></li>
    <li>Locate the <strong>Salary Proration</strong> section in the table</li>
    <li>Click the <strong>Edit</strong> button (pencil icon) to open the configuration modal</li>
    <li>In the modal, find the <strong>Calculation Basis</strong> dropdown field</li>
    <li>Click the dropdown to view available options:
      <ul style="margin: 10px 0; padding-left: 20px;">
        <li><strong>Working Days</strong> - Excludes weekends and public holidays</li>
        <li><strong>Calendar Days</strong> - All days in the month (typically 30 or 31)</li>
        <li><strong>Custom Days</strong> - <span class="citation" data-source="zendesk" data-ref="14243704039185">Most UAE and KSA companies use 30 custom days to align with labor law</span></li>
      </ul>
    </li>
    <li>Select your preferred calculation basis</li>
  </ol>

  <figure class="screenshot-container">
    <img src="validation/screenshots/09-salary-proration-calc-basis-dropdown.png" alt="Dropdown menu showing three calculation basis options: Working days, Calendar days, and Custom days" class="screenshot">
    <figcaption>Setup Phase 1 - All three calculation basis options available: Working days, Calendar days, Custom days</figcaption>
  </figure>

  <h4>Phase 2: Choose Salary Components</h4>
  
  <p><span class="citation" data-source="zendesk" data-ref="14243704039185">Select which salary components to factor into daily wage calculations</span>.</p>

  <ol class="step-list">
    <li>In the same configuration modal, locate the <strong>Salary Components</strong> section</li>
    <li>Choose one of the following options:
      <ul style="margin: 10px 0; padding-left: 20px;">
        <li><strong>Basic Salary Only</strong> - Uses only the base salary for calculations</li>
        <li><strong>Basic Salary + Allowances</strong> - Includes all allowances in the calculation</li>
      </ul>
    </li>
    <li>The selected option will apply to salary proration, leave encashment, and unpaid leave deductions</li>
  </ol>

  <figure class="screenshot-container">
    <img src="validation/screenshots/08-salary-proration-modal-details.png" alt="Salary proration configuration modal showing salary components selection and daily wage formula" class="screenshot">
    <figcaption>Setup Phase 2 - Salary components selection interface visible: Basic salary + allowances configuration shown in salary proration modal with daily wage formula</figcaption>
  </figure>

  <div class="info-box">
    <h4>Understanding the Daily Wage Formula</h4>
    <p>The system displays the daily wage calculation formula based on your selections. For example: <strong>Basic Salary + Allowances ÷ 30 Custom Days = Daily Wage Rate</strong></p>
    <p style="color: #6B7280; font-size: 14px; margin-top: 8px;">This formula is used for salary proration, leave encashment, and unpaid leave deductions throughout the payroll cycle.</p>
  </div>

  <h4>Phase 3: Configure End of Service (EOS) Settings</h4>
  
  <p><span class="citation" data-source="zendesk" data-ref="14243768433425">Super admins can configure and customize leave encashment policies for end-of-service calculations</span>.</p>

  <ol class="step-list">
    <li>Navigate to <strong>Settings > Payroll > End of Service Eligibility</strong></li>
    <li>Review the table showing all configured leave types (Sick, Vacation45, etc.)</li>
    <li>Click the <strong>Edit</strong> button for the leave type you want to configure</li>
    <li>In the configuration modal, verify the <strong>Salary Components</strong> setting:
      <ul style="margin: 10px 0; padding-left: 20px;">
        <li>Basic Only</li>
        <li>Basic + Allowances</li>
      </ul>
    </li>
    <li>Verify the <strong>Calculation Method</strong> (should match your Daily Wage Calculation settings)</li>
    <li>Review the <strong>Number of Days</strong> field for the pro-rated amount</li>
    <li>Click <strong>Save</strong> to apply the configuration</li>
  </ol>

  <figure class="screenshot-container">
    <img src="validation/screenshots/10-eos-eligibility-table.png" alt="End of Service eligibility configuration table showing leave types and their daily wage formulas" class="screenshot">
    <figcaption>Setup Phase 3 - End of Service eligibility configuration accessible from Settings > Payroll with daily wage formula displayed for each leave type</figcaption>
  </figure>

  <figure class="screenshot-container">
    <img src="validation/screenshots/11-eos-config-modal-vacation45.png" alt="EOS configuration modal for Vacation45 leave type showing salary components, calculation method, and override indicator" class="screenshot">
    <figcaption>Setup Phase 3 (continued) - Leave type configuration interface with salary component options, calculation method selection, and override indicator showing global configuration precedence</figcaption>
  </figure>

  <div class="info-box warning">
    <h4>Override Indicator Alert</h4>
    <p>When configuring EOS settings, you may see an alert stating: <strong>"Daily rate is configured in daily wage calculation setting"</strong>. This indicates that the global Daily Wage Calculation settings take precedence over individual leave type configurations. Click the <strong>View</strong> button to review the global settings if needed.</p>
  </div>

  <h4>Phase 4: Configure Unpaid Leave Deductions</h4>
  
  <p><span class="citation" data-source="zendesk" data-ref="14244040988689">Configure unpaid leave deduction calculation when adding a new leave policy</span>.</p>

  <ol class="step-list">
    <li>Navigate to <strong>Settings > Leaves > Leave Policies</strong></li>
    <li>Click <strong>Add New Policy</strong> or edit an existing policy</li>
    <li>In the leave policy form, locate the <strong>Unpaid Leave</strong> option</li>
    <li>Select <strong>Unpaid Leave</strong> to enable deduction configuration</li>
    <li>The system will display the <strong>Calculation Method</strong> dropdown (this is controlled by Daily Wage Calculation settings)</li>
    <li>Note: The formula fields will be <strong>greyed out/disabled</strong> because the calculation is managed globally through Daily Wage Calculation settings</li>
    <li>Review the remarks section showing the daily rate formula</li>
    <li>Click <strong>Save</strong> to apply the unpaid leave configuration</li>
  </ol>

  <figure class="screenshot-container">
    <img src="validation/screenshots/06-leave-pay-rate-unpaid-config.png" alt="Leave policy configuration showing unpaid leave option with disabled formula fields and override indicator" class="screenshot">
    <figcaption>Setup Phase 4 - Unpaid Leave option configuration with formula fields disabled (greyed out) indicating global Daily Wage Calculation settings control the calculation</figcaption>
  </figure>

  <div class="info-box">
    <h4>Greyed Out Fields Explanation</h4>
    <p><span class="citation" data-source="zendesk" data-ref="14244040988689">When unpaid leave deduction calculation is configured, the formula fields (Basic salary dropdown, Custom days dropdown, and number field) are disabled</span>. This ensures consistency across all payroll calculations and prevents conflicting configurations.</p>
  </div>

  <h4>Phase 5: Save and Apply Changes</h4>
  
  <ol class="step-list">
    <li>After completing all configuration phases, review your selections:
      <ul style="margin: 10px 0; padding-left: 20px;">
        <li>Calculation Basis (Working Days, Calendar Days, or Custom Days)</li>
        <li>Salary Components (Basic Only or Basic + Allowances)</li>
        <li>EOS leave type configurations</li>
        <li>Unpaid leave policy settings</li>
      </ul>
    </li>
    <li>Click the <strong>Save</strong> button in each configuration modal</li>
    <li>The system will apply these settings to all active payroll calculations</li>
  </ol>

  <div class="info-box warning">
    <h4>Important: Open Payroll Month Consideration</h4>
    <p><span class="citation" data-source="zendesk" data-ref="14243760419089">When payroll month is open and prorated salary transactions exist, super admin must reject existing prorated salary transactions before saving new proration settings</span>. If you see a prompt to reject existing transactions, follow the on-screen instructions to proceed.</p>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="section">
  <h2>8. Feature Usage</h2>

  <h3>Common Workflows</h3>

  <h4>Workflow 1: Processing Unpaid Leave Requests</h4>
  
  <p><span class="citation" data-source="zendesk" data-ref="14154746403601">To calculate and deduct daily pay for employees taking unpaid leave, the system determines the appropriate salary reduction based on the number of working or calendar days</span>.</p>

  <ol class="step-list">
    <li>An employee submits an unpaid leave request through the leave management system</li>
    <li>Review and <strong>approve</strong> the unpaid leave request</li>
    <li>The system automatically calculates the daily pay deduction using the configured Daily Wage Calculation settings</li>
    <li>The deduction is generated and reflected in the payroll table</li>
    <li>During payroll processing, the deduction is automatically applied to the employee's salary</li>
  </ol>

  <div class="info-box success">
    <h4>Success Indicator</h4>
    <p><span class="citation" data-source="zendesk" data-ref="14154746403601">Automatic pay deduction is reflected on the payroll table, showing the calculated daily pay rate for unpaid leave</span>. You should see the deduction amount appear in the employee's payroll record.</p>
  </div>

  <h4>Workflow 2: Calculating Salary Proration for New Employees</h4>
  
  <p><span class="citation" data-source="zendesk" data-ref="14243760419089">Salary proration adjusts and calculates an employee's salary proportionally based on the actual days worked, affecting their first salary and end-of-service settlement</span>.</p>

  <ol class="step-list">
    <li>When a new employee joins mid-month, their first salary is automatically prorated</li>
    <li>The system uses the configured calculation basis (Working Days, Calendar Days, or Custom Days) to determine the number of days worked</li>
    <li>The daily wage rate is calculated: <strong>Total Salary ÷ Number of Days = Daily Rate</strong></li>
    <li>The daily rate is multiplied by actual days worked to generate the prorated salary</li>
    <li>The prorated amount appears in the payroll table for the employee's first month</li>
  </ol>

  <div class="info-box">
    <h4>Month Length Variations</h4>
    <p><span class="citation" data-source="zendesk" data-ref="14243704039185">Calculation varies depending on month length (e.g., 31 days in January, 28 days in February)</span>. The system automatically accounts for these variations when calculating daily wage rates.</p>
  </div>

  <h4>Workflow 3: Configuring Leave Encashment for End-of-Service</h4>
  
  <p><span class="citation" data-source="zendesk" data-ref="14243768433425">Super admins can configure and customize leave encashment policies for end-of-service calculations</span>.</p>

  <ol class="step-list">
    <li>Navigate to <strong>Settings > Payroll > End of Service Eligibility</strong></li>
    <li>Identify the leave types eligible for encashment (e.g., Vacation45, Sick Leave)</li>
    <li>For each leave type, configure:
      <ul style="margin: 10px 0; padding-left: 20px;">
        <li>Salary components to include (Basic Only or Basic + Allowances)</li>
        <li>Calculation method (should align with Daily Wage Calculation settings)</li>
        <li>Number of days for pro-rated calculation</li>
      </ul>
    </li>
    <li>When an employee exits, the system automatically calculates leave encashment using these settings</li>
    <li>The encashment amount is included in the final settlement payment</li>
  </ol>

  <div class="info-box success">
    <h4>Success Indicator</h4>
    <p><span class="citation" data-source="zendesk" data-ref="14243768433425">Customized leave encashment policy affects end-of-service calculations</span>. When processing an employee's exit, you should see the leave encashment amount calculated and included in their final settlement.</p>
  </div>

  <h3>Key Calculation Rules</h3>

  <div class="card">
    <h4>Daily Pay Calculation Formula</h4>
    <p><span class="citation" data-source="zendesk" data-ref="14154746403601">Daily pay is calculated by dividing total salary by number of actual working days</span>.</p>
    <p style="margin-top: 12px; padding: 12px; background-color: #F3EEFF; border-radius: 6px; font-family: 'Courier New', monospace; color: #5A2B99;">
      <strong>Daily Pay = Total Salary ÷ Number of Days</strong>
    </p>
  </div>

  <div class="card">
    <h4>Working Days Calculation</h4>
    <p><span class="citation" data-source="zendesk" data-ref="14154746403601">Public holidays are deducted from working days</span>. When using the "Working Days" calculation basis, the system automatically excludes weekends and public holidays from the day count.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="card">
    <h4>Calculation Basis Options</h4>
    <p><span class="citation" data-source="zendesk" data-ref="14243704039185">Calculation can be based on calendar days, working days, or custom days, and can exclude weekends and public holidays</span>.</p>
  </div>

  <h3>Edge Cases & Troubleshooting</h3>

  <div class="info-box warning">
    <h4>Public Holiday Handling</h4>
    <p><span class="citation" data-source="zendesk" data-ref="14154746403601">Public holidays must be considered and subtracted from working days when calculating daily pay</span>. Ensure your public holiday calendar is properly configured in Settings before processing payroll.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="info-box warning">
    <h4>Open Payroll Month Changes</h4>
    <p><span class="citation" data-source="zendesk" data-ref="14243760419089">When payroll month is open and prorated salary transactions exist, super admin must manually reject and resave transactions</span> if you need to change the Daily Wage Calculation settings. The system will prompt you to do this if necessary.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="info-box">
    <h4>Calculation Method Impact</h4>
    <p><span class="citation" data-source="zendesk" data-ref="14243704039185">Different calculation methods can impact final wage calculations</span>. For example, using "Custom Days (30)" will produce different results than "Calendar Days" in months with 31 days. Choose the method that aligns with your company's labor law requirements.</p>
  </div>

  <h3>Verification Checklist</h3>

  <p>After implementing the Daily Wage Calculator, verify the following:</p>

  <ol class="step-list">
    <li>✓ Calculation basis is set correctly (Working Days, Calendar Days, or Custom Days)</li>
    <li>✓ Salary components are selected appropriately (Basic Only or Basic + Allowances)</li>
    <li>✓ Public holiday calendar is configured and up-to-date</li>
    <li>✓ EOS leave type configurations are complete for all eligible leave types</li>
    <li>✓ Unpaid leave policies are configured with the correct deduction settings</li>
    <li>✓ Test payroll calculations show correct daily wage rates</li>
    <li>✓ Salary proration is applied correctly for new employees</li>
    <li>✓ Leave encashment calculations are accurate for end-of-service scenarios</li>
  </ol>

</section>
      
      <!-- Section 3: Reference & Troubleshooting -->
      <section class="reference-troubleshooting">
  <!-- Section 9: Feature Maintenance -->
  <div class="section">
    <h2>Feature Maintenance</h2>
    
    <div class="subsection">
      <h3>Regular Review Schedule</h3>
      <p><span class="citation" data-source="zendesk" data-ref="14243704039185">The Daily Wage Calculator configuration should be reviewed whenever there are changes to your company's public holiday calendar or labor law requirements</span>. We recommend:</p>
      
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Monthly:</strong> Verify that public holidays are correctly excluded from working day calculations</li>
        <li><strong>Quarterly:</strong> Review salary component selections to ensure they align with current compensation structure</li>
        <li><strong>Annually:</strong> Audit all calculation bases (calendar days, working days, custom days) against labor law updates for your jurisdiction</li>
        <li><strong>As needed:</strong> Update configuration when leave policies or end-of-service eligibility rules change</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <div class="subsection">
      <h3>Best Practices</h3>
      <ul>
        <li><span class="citation" data-source="zendesk" data-ref="14243704039185">Most UAE and KSA companies use 30 custom days to align with labor law</span> – consider this standard unless your organization has specific requirements</li>
        <li>Document your chosen calculation method and communicate it clearly to payroll and HR teams</li>
        <li><span class="citation" data-source="zendesk" data-ref="14243760419089">When payroll month is open and prorated salary transactions exist, manually reject and resave transactions before updating proration settings</span></li>
        <li>Test configuration changes in a non-production environment first, if available</li>
        <li>Maintain records of all configuration changes for audit purposes</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Section 10: Business Rules & Limitations -->
  <div class="section">
    <h2>Business Rules & Limitations</h2>
    
    <div class="subsection">
      <h3>Daily Pay Calculation Rules</h3>
      <p><span class="citation" data-source="zendesk" data-ref="14154746403601">Daily pay is calculated by dividing total salary by the number of actual working days</span>. The following rules govern all calculations:</p>
      
      <table class="rules-table">
        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th>Rule</th>
            <th>Description</th>
            <th>Impact</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr>
            <td>Calculation Base Selection</td>
            <td><span class="citation" data-source="zendesk" data-ref="14243704039185">Can use calendar days (30 days), working days (e.g., 22 days), or custom days</span></td>
            <td>Directly affects daily wage rate and all downstream calculations</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Public Holiday Deduction</td>
            <td><span class="citation" data-source="zendesk" data-ref="14154746403601">Public holidays are deducted from working days</span></td>
            <td>Increases daily wage rate by reducing denominator</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Salary Component Inclusion</td>
            <td><span class="citation" data-source="zendesk" data-ref="14243704039185">Can choose Basic Only or Basic + Allowances for calculations</span></td>
            <td>Determines which salary components are factored into daily rate</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Month Length Variation</td>
            <td><span class="citation" data-source="zendesk" data-ref="14243704039185">Calculation varies depending on month length (e.g., 31 days in January, 28 days in February)</span></td>
            <td>Calendar day calculations will differ month-to-month</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Unpaid Leave Deduction</td>
            <td><span class="citation" data-source="zendesk" data-ref="14244040988689">Unpaid leave deductions must be calculated daily and set off against the employee's monthly pay</span></td>
            <td>Reduces employee's monthly salary based on approved unpaid leave days</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Payroll Impact</td>
            <td><span class="citation" data-source="zendesk" data-ref="14243760419089">Changes will affect all active (unpaid) amounts in the payroll table</span></td>
            <td>Configuration updates may require transaction rejections and recalculations</td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>

    <div class="subsection">
      <h3>Calculation Logic Overview</h3>
      <p>The Daily Wage Calculator applies the following logic across all use cases:</p>
      
      <div class="calculation-formula">
        <p><strong>Basic Formula:</strong></p>
        <p style="font-family: 'Courier New', monospace; background-color: #F3EEFF; padding: 12px; border-radius: 6px; border-left: 4px solid #9647FF;">
          Daily Wage = (Selected Salary Components) ÷ (Calculation Base Days - Public Holidays)
        </p>
      </div>

      <p><strong>Application Scenarios:</strong></p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Salary Proration:</strong> <span class="citation" data-source="zendesk" data-ref="14243760419089">Adjusts employee's salary proportionally based on actual days worked, affecting their first salary and end-of-service settlement</span></li>
        <li><strong>Leave Encashment:</strong> <span class="citation" data-source="zendesk" data-ref="14243768433425">Customizable policies for end-of-service calculations based on selected salary components and calculation method</span></li>
        <li><strong>Unpaid Leave Deduction:</strong> <span class="citation" data-source="zendesk" data-ref="14154746403601">Determines appropriate salary reduction based on number of working or calendar days</span></li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <div class="subsection">
      <h3>Configuration Constraints</h3>
      <table class="rules-table">
        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th>Constraint</th>
            <th>Details</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr>
            <td>Calculation Base is Mandatory</td>
            <td>Must select one: Calendar Days, Working Days, or Custom Days</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Salary Component Selection</td>
            <td>Must choose at least one component: Basic Only or Basic + Allowances</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Public Holiday Calendar Required</td>
            <td>Company-specific public holiday calendar must be configured for accurate working day calculations</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Leave Policy Configuration</td>
            <td><span class="citation" data-source="zendesk" data-ref="14244040988689">Unpaid leave deduction calculation must be configured when adding a new leave policy</span></td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Active Payroll Transactions</td>
            <td><span class="citation" data-source="zendesk" data-ref="14243760419089">When payroll month is open, super admin must reject existing prorated salary transactions before saving new proration settings</span></td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Section 11: Troubleshooting & Edge Cases -->
  <div class="section">
    <h2>Troubleshooting & Edge Cases</h2>
    
    <div class="subsection">
      <h3>Common Issues and Solutions</h3>

      <div class="info-box warning">
        <h4>Issue: Payroll Month is Open with Existing Prorated Transactions</h4>
        <p><strong>Symptom:</strong> Unable to save changes to Daily Wage Calculator configuration</p>
        <p><strong>Root Cause:</strong> <span class="citation" data-source="zendesk" data-ref="14243760419089">When payroll month is open and prorated salary transactions exist, the system prevents configuration changes to protect data integrity</span></p>
        <p><strong>Solution:</strong></p>
        <ol>
          <li>Navigate to the Payroll table</li>
          <li>Locate all active (unpaid) prorated salary transactions</li>
          <li>Reject each transaction individually</li>
          <li>Return to Settings > Payroll > Daily Wage Calculation</li>
          <li>Update your configuration</li>
          <li>The system will automatically recalculate and regenerate prorated salary transactions</li>
        </ol>
      </div>

      <div class="info-box warning">
        <h4>Issue: Incorrect Daily Wage Calculations After Configuration Change</h4>
        <p><strong>Symptom:</strong> Daily wage rates appear incorrect or inconsistent across employees</p>
        <p><strong>Root Cause:</strong> <span class="citation" data-source="zendesk" data-ref="14243704039185">Different calculation methods can impact final wage calculations, and month length variations affect calendar day calculations</span></p>
        <p><strong>Solution:</strong></p>
        <ol>
          <li>Verify your selected calculation base matches your company's policy (Calendar Days, Working Days, or Custom Days)</li>
          <li>Confirm public holidays are correctly configured in your company calendar</li>
          <li>Check that the correct salary components are selected (Basic Only vs. Basic + Allowances)</li>
          <li>For month-specific variations, note that <span class="citation" data-source="zendesk" data-ref="14243704039185">calculation varies depending on month length (e.g., 31 days in January, 28 days in February)</span></li>
          <li>If using custom days, ensure the value aligns with your labor law requirements</li>
        </ol>
      </div>

      <div class="info-box warning">
        <h4>Issue: Unpaid Leave Deductions Not Appearing on Payroll</h4>
        <p><strong>Symptom:</strong> Approved unpaid leave is not reducing employee salary</p>
        <p><strong>Root Cause:</strong> Unpaid leave deduction calculation may not be configured for the leave policy</p>
        <p><strong>Solution:</strong></p>
        <ol>
          <li>Navigate to Settings > Leaves > Leave Policies</li>
          <li>Select the leave policy being used</li>
          <li>Verify that the "Unpaid Leave" option is enabled</li>
          <li>Confirm the calculation method (Basic Only or Basic + Allowances) is selected</li>
          <li>Verify the day calculation type matches your Daily Wage Calculator settings</li>
          <li>Re-approve the unpaid leave request to trigger recalculation</li>
        </ol>
      </div>

      <div class="info-box warning">
        <h4>Issue: End-of-Service Leave Encashment Calculations Seem Incorrect</h4>
        <p><strong>Symptom:</strong> Leave encashment amounts don't match expected values</p>
        <p><strong>Root Cause:</strong> <span class="citation" data-source="zendesk" data-ref="14243768433425">Super admins can see which eligible paid leave-type policies will be overwritten</span> – configuration conflicts may exist</p>
        <p><strong>Solution:</strong></p>
        <ol>
          <li>Navigate to Settings > Payroll > End of Service Eligibility</li>
          <li>Review the configuration modal for any warnings about overwritten policies</li>
          <li>Verify salary component selection (Basic Only vs. Basic + Allowances)</li>
          <li>Confirm calculation method matches your Daily Wage Calculator settings</li>
          <li>Check that all eligible leave types are correctly configured for encashment</li>
          <li>Review the End of Service Eligibility table to confirm settings</li>
        </ol>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="subsection">
      <h3>Edge Cases and Warnings</h3>

      <div class="info-box warning">
        <h4>Public Holiday Handling</h4>
        <p><span class="citation" data-source="zendesk" data-ref="14154746403601">Public holidays must be considered and subtracted from working days when calculating daily pay</span>. This is critical for accurate calculations:</p>
        <ul>
          <li>Ensure your company's public holiday calendar is up-to-date</li>
          <li>When using "Working Days" calculation base, verify that public holidays are automatically excluded</li>
          <li>If using "Custom Days," manually account for public holidays in your day count</li>
          <li>Different emirates and countries may have different public holidays – confirm your calendar is jurisdiction-specific</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <div class="info-box warning">
        <h4>Month Length Variations</h4>
        <p><span class="citation" data-source="zendesk" data-ref="14243704039185">Calculation varies depending on month length (e.g., 31 days in January, 28 days in February)</span>. When using Calendar Days:</p>
        <ul>
          <li>Daily wage rates will naturally vary month-to-month</li>
          <li>February calculations will result in higher daily rates due to fewer days</li>
          <li>This is expected behavior and reflects actual working days</li>
          <li>Consider using "Custom Days" (typically 30) for consistent monthly calculations</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <div class="info-box warning">
        <h4>Salary Component Misalignment</h4>
        <p>Ensure consistency across all wage calculation features:</p>
        <ul>
          <li>If Daily Wage Calculator uses "Basic + Allowances," ensure Leave Encashment and Unpaid Leave configurations use the same</li>
          <li>Misaligned salary components across features can result in inconsistent calculations</li>
          <li>Document your chosen salary component approach and apply it uniformly</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <div class="info-box warning">
        <h4>Configuration Change Impact</h4>
        <p><span class="citation" data-source="zendesk" data-ref="14243760419089">Changes will affect all active (unpaid) amounts in the payroll table</span>. Before making configuration changes:</p>
        <ul>
          <li>Identify all open payroll months with active transactions</li>
          <li>Plan configuration changes during payroll closure periods when possible</li>
          <li>If changes are necessary during open payroll, be prepared to reject and recalculate affected transactions</li>
          <li>Communicate changes to payroll team to prevent confusion</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

